---
title: "Angular Console App Standards"
description: "Guidelines for developing and maintaining the Angular frontend in the console/ directory."
tags: [angular, frontend, standards, typescript, coreui]
---

## Core Principles
- Use Angular 18+ features, including standalone components and modern dependency injection.
- Structure code by feature: use folders for views, modals, layout, shared, services, and utils.
- Prefer CoreUI components for UI consistency and accessibility.
- Use SCSS for styling; keep styles modular and component-scoped.
- Use strict TypeScript settings and type everything explicitly.
- Keep business logic in services, not components.
- Use RxJS for async flows; prefer `takeUntilDestroyed` for subscriptions.
- Use Angular Router for navigation; configure routes in `app.routes.ts`.

## API & State Management
- Use dedicated services for API communication (e.g., `BackendService`, `ConfigService`, `AuthService`).
- Store credentials securely in localStorage/sessionStorage; never hardcode secrets.
- API base path is loaded from `assets/app.config.json` via `ConfigService`.
- Use DTOs for all backend communication; keep client-side models in sync with backend contracts.

## UI & UX
- Use CoreUI's `IconSetService` for icon management.
- Set document title via `Title` service in root component.
- Use color mode and theme management via CoreUI's `ColorModeService`.
- Use modular, reusable components in `components/` and `shared/`.
- Keep templates clean; avoid logic in HTML.

## Testing
- Use Karma/Jasmine for unit tests; place specs alongside components/services.
- Test business logic in services, not components.
- Keep tests deterministic and isolated.

## Configuration
- All configuration files (e.g., `app.config.json`) go in `assets/`.
- Use `app.config.ts` for application-wide providers and initialization.

## Code Quality
- Use `editorconfig` and Prettier for formatting.
- Follow Angular and TypeScript best practices for naming, structure, and imports.
- Keep code DRY; extract repeated logic into utils or shared services.
- Document complex logic with comments and JSDoc.

## Commit & Review
- Keep frontend changes in separate commits from backend.
- Update this file when standards change or new patterns are introduced.

## Example Directory Structure
```
console/
  src/
    app/
      api-client/
      components/
      icons/
      layout/
      modals/
      services/
      shared/
      utils.ts
      views/
    assets/
    scss/
    index.html
    main.ts
    test.ts
  angular.json
  package.json
  tsconfig.json
  karma.conf.js
```
